The activity aims at supporting the Culture Sector's communication on its strategic priorities and flagship projects by reaching out to its various networks and partners.

The overall purpose of the project is to support the government's efforts in increasing access and improving the quality of girls' education through capacity building and targeted interventions at both institutional and community level.

Geographically, the project will target the most disenfranchised and hardest to reach areas of Pakistan where girls' access to primary education are most challenged and has high illiteracy rate of adults particularly among women.

Budget to support the Executive Office functions in providing strategic advice, quality control and management support to the ADG and overall coordination of the development, implementation and monitoring of the approved programme and budget of the Culture Sector, as well as the Sector's communication with other Sectors/Bureaux/Offices at UNESCO, with other agencies of the UN System and with external partners.

The Culture|2030 Indicators is a framework of thematic indicators whose purpose is to measure and monitor the progress of culture's enabling contribution to the national and local implementation of the Goals and Targets of the 2030 Agenda for Sustainable Development.

Participation in the Regional Coordination Mechanism (RCM) Africa, Cluster 8, sub-cluster for culture and presentation of the UNESCO Culture programme contributing to the Aspiration 5 of the African Union Agenda 2063 as well as integrating any other relevant UN activity in this domain.

The "Special account for the support of the Culture Programme activities" was established by Executive Board's decision 202 EX/30 (II) with a view to mobilizing flexible funding for Major Programme IV - Culture. The purpose is to attract pooled funding from donors in direct reinforcement of the programme approved by the General Conference with as little earmarking as possible. To make the special account attractive, donors will be able to earmark their funding to any level of the C/5, i.e. Major Programme, Main Line of Action or Expected Result, but not below.

Following up on the Ministers' Forum organized in November 2019, APA/FOs have agreed to organize an Asia-Pacific Forum on Culture and Sustainable Development during the 2020-2021 biennium. The Forum will further deliberate issues relevant to the Asia-Pacific region and to develop common actions for moving forward.

Language is perhaps the most distinctive and defining feature of any human society. It is pivotal in the realm of information technology, the tool that all modern sectors use, and the foundation on which modern human communication is established. 
With the aim to enhance multilinguism, and address the many-faceted relations between Arabic and the system of knowledge acquisition, a set of activities will be implemented in the following categories: Publications /Translation of existing material ; Activities/initiatives to promote the Arabic Language; Production and dissemination of Knowledge in Arabic; Web and Media; Interpretation in Arabic

As the follow-up of the decision of the First ICC-Angkor, held in Tokyo in 1993, the working procedures of the Committee were established. It was decided that the Committee would be co-chaired by France and Japan in collaboration with the APSARA Authority, UNESCO provides the Secretariat. It was reconfirmed by the Angkor International Conference recently held in Cambodia on 5/12/2013 where the French and Japan co-Chairs have re-endorsed their co-chairmanship.
The financial mechanism established on the initiative of Japan and France also foresaw that the cost of the ICC-Angkor meetings should be borne by these two countries.
